In fact, I know that I even got more lucky than some of my colleagues, since the comments for me are at least mostly of a political nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and purposefulness of those colleagues who face sexist or racist rhetoric every day without being afraid of it.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults have become the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour should embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is no longer wide-spread, with every sign of mistrust or change in the rules of choice becoming more narrow-minded.
Over the past two years, I have received many advices to keep quiet, not to talk so much and that then “everything will be fine”.
But that’s not why I got into politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student provoked by the Thatcher government, which through its neglect led to the literal collapse of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local councillor or as a minister.
I have never concealed my political views, including during the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political stance and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would like to say that when the state heads for Brexit, it will harm households, businesses and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the Labour leader.
But in reality, my message is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threats of recall or political excommunication will prevent me from acting in the way I consider best in protecting your interests.
Krisley Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
