“The sea is ours”: Bolivia hopes that the ship will reopen the way to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors are constantly patrolling the rigging of La Paz Marine Headquarters.
An ocean blue flag flies over public buildings.
Sea bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: “The sea belongs to us by right.
It is our duty to get it back.”
In all of Bolivia, which has no access to the ocean, the memory of the lost exit handed over to Chile after a bloody conflict in the 19th century is still alive – as is the call to sail again across the Pacific.
In fact, that hope is currently the strongest in decades, while Bolivia is awaiting a judgment by an international court on October 1, after five years of deliberation.
"The strength is in Bolivia, there is a sense of serenity and unity everywhere, and the country expects a positive result," said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the international court on the big screen across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will support Bolivia's claim and that after decades of negotiations, Chile will be obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the ocean.
Evo Morales, the charismatic local president of Bolivia who is set to head to a contested re-election battle next year, also put a lot of weight on Monday's judgement.
“We are very close to regain access to the Pacific Ocean,” Morales said last August.
But some analysts believe that the court's likelihood of deciding in Bolivia's favor is quite small, and even if it did decide in her favor, it would not change things in reality.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to seize Chilean territory and has ruled that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the international court’s verdict is just six months after hearing the latest arguments indicates that the case is “not complicated,” said Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And instead of contributing to Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have actually hurt her.
“The problem of access to the ocean has been exacerbated by the current government of Bolivia,” Zarate said.
He then hinted that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric had wiped out Chile’s remaining goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to have a normal dialogue after what happened.
The two countries have not held diplomatic missions to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court’s decision was being taken unusually quickly.
He said on Monday Bolivia would have "an incredible opportunity to open the page of a new era in its relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreement by achieving benefits for both sides".
Kalzadilla also rejected the idea that Morales — who continues to be one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the problem of access to the ocean as a “political crutch.”
“Bolivia will never relinquish its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“Judgment is an opportunity to see that we must overcome our past problems.”
