John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another excellent performance of exam scores that is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports disciplines, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen careers and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can draw up and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language that you understand, your words will reach them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year’s exams, we see that languages are the most successful for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A score.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students scored A in Chinese, with the same score being scored by 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice on the part of students receive the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Work Skills Commission found that 17% of employers found it difficult to find employees because of insufficient language skills.
Therefore, proficiency in foreign languages is becoming increasingly mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more job positions require the proficiency of a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masters a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one breast ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, and French was the only language whose proficiency reached a double-digit rate of 15%.
That is why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ from one language to another.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered more important to the UK in a future plan by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child may have, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should be really considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
