North Korea says 'no way' to disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened distrust of the United States and there was no way the country would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong-hou said “significant goodwill measures” had been taken over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, destroying a nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trusting the United States, we will not believe in our own national security, and under no circumstances will we be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri expressed North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “step-by-step” approach to eliminating nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking step-by-step measures, his statement seemed meaningful as it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for “nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula” and Trump gave assurances of North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for easing strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States is pushing for ‘nuclear weapons first’ and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and even objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can make us fall to our knees is a meaningless dream of those who don’t know us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea, not the United States, the elimination of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a standstill.
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that the targeting of North Korean missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “evil President” Trump called Kim “a man-missile” on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with “complete destruction,” praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea removes its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there is no deadline for this and said: “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “implementation of the Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament takes place.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in a bid to halt funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip went well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, but only a few hours later North Korea accused him of making “gangster demands.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea vowed to destroy a missile site and nuclear complex if the U.S. takes “appropriate measures.”
According to him, Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore and that he wanted to achieve normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is causing all students to sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning “all night long” with the help of caffeine.
A faculty member found that the world’s number one university students often don’t even think about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Kaysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has prepared what he believes is the first course of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
Finally, a girl came to me and said, “Why are they telling me this now, in my last year?”
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, explains to students the most important things about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic achievement, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
Another part of the participants described how long-term sleep deprivation could increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” added Prof. Keisler.
A culture of pride in “all night learning” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate and quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he says – even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, causing them to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaysler draft the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says his course "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining a competing institution.
Professor Kaysler recommended that students think about setting a sleep and wake alarm and know the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
