Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and counting... the day the future physicist Johann Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
A cornerstone of science since then, the Geiger counter also became a cornerstone of pop culture when the 1950 film The Bells of Coronado, featuring the seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, was released.
Man: "What the hell is this?
Rogers: This is a Geiger counter and is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
