Fishing and farming are the foundations of the economy of central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal area of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important for the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongala have been hit several times by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongal.
A tsunami struck the western part of Dongal in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic "Pacific Ring of Fire" and is regularly mowed by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A powerful earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra triggered a tsunami wave that struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the entire Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
